In Week 22, the story of American democracy turned on how power met resistance, and how far the state was willing to go to keep that resistance in check. The week was marked by mass civic mobilization under the banner of \'93No Kings,\'94 by a political assassination that brought the threat of violence into the homes of elected officials, and by a presidency that treated law, force, and memory as tools to be bent toward its own survival. At the same time, courts, some lawmakers, and millions of ordinary people tried to hold a line. The Democracy Clock, which had stood at 7:51 p.m., moved forward to 7:54 p.m. The three-minute shift did not reflect a single dramatic break, but rather the way many separate acts\'97raids, rulings, firings, and symbols\'97combined to narrow the space in which democratic life can breathe.\
\
The previous week had closed with the clock at 7:51 p.m., already well past the calm of an early evening democracy. By the end of Week 22 it read 7:54 p.m., a net move of 2.3 minutes toward midnight. The movement came from several converging patterns. Executive power pushed more openly against legal and institutional limits, from the federalization of state National Guard units to unilateral delays of laws upheld by the Supreme Court. Law enforcement and immigration powers were used not as neutral instruments but as weapons against disfavored cities, officials, and communities. Protest rights were formally recognized yet practically constrained by curfews, teargas, and threats of vehicular violence. Political violence moved from threat to deed with the killing of a Minnesota legislator, while disinformation tried to invert blame. And beneath it all, the administration worked to reshape memory and information\'97through mass layoffs at Voice of America, the rollback of Juneteenth and DEI recognition, and the quiet removal of civil-rights symbols from public spaces. These shifts, taken together, justified the clock\'92s advance.\
\
The most visible struggle over power inside the United States played out in Los Angeles and other Democratic-led cities, where immigration enforcement and military deployment merged. President Trump had already ordered ICE to intensify raids in what he called \'93Democrat Power Centers,\'94 and this week those orders took concrete form. Agents swept through Home Depot parking lots, swap meets, churches, schools, and Latino neighborhoods in Los Angeles and Lake Worth Beach, Florida, detaining not only undocumented workers but also U.S. citizens and long-settled residents. The raids were not confined to workplaces; they reached into parishes and classrooms, places once treated as sensitive. The effect was to turn everyday spaces into zones of fear. People stopped going to work, kept children home from school, and avoided public life. In these communities, the law no longer felt like a shield. It felt like a net.\
\
When protests rose in response, the administration did not step back. It sent in troops. In Los Angeles, Trump deployed thousands of National Guard soldiers and hundreds of Marines over the objection of California\'92s governor. This was the first time since the mid-1960s that a president had federalized state forces to police a city without state consent. A federal district judge ordered control of the Guard returned to the governor, but the Ninth Circuit stayed that ruling and later sided with Trump, allowing federal control to continue. Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth hinted he might not comply even if the courts ruled against him. The legal back-and-forth mattered, but on the ground the message was simple: the president could put troops in American streets to enforce his preferred policies, and the courts might not stop him in time. The trait that measures whether security forces protect people or power moved sharply toward midnight.\
\
The same pattern appeared in how law enforcement treated political figures who stood with immigrants. In New York, city comptroller and mayoral candidate Brad Lander was arrested by ICE and FBI agents outside immigration court as he tried to accompany a Spanish-speaking immigrant whose case had been dismissed. Agents accused him of assaulting law enforcement, but video showed officers roughly handling him while he asked about a warrant. He was held for hours and then released without charges. Days later, DHS issued guidance requiring members of Congress to give 72 hours\'92 notice before visiting detention centers, despite a federal law granting them unannounced access. New York representatives Jerry Nadler and Dan Goldman were turned away from an ICE facility even after requesting a visit. These moves did not just inconvenience oversight; they signaled that those who tried to look inside the machinery of detention could themselves become targets of that machinery.\
\
The law itself was bent to serve power in more subtle ways. The Environmental Protection Agency dropped a major enforcement case against the private prison company Geo Group, which had faced millions in fines for using a toxic disinfectant on detainees and staff, after the company made significant donations to Trump and Republican leaders. In the financial realm, the Securities and Exchange Commission dismissed a lawsuit against Binance, the world\'92s largest crypto exchange, soon after a Trump family token appeared on its platform, and the administration loosened cryptocurrency regulations in ways that paused or ended a dozen fraud cases. At the same time, a House Judiciary report estimated that Trump\'92s pardons had cost taxpayers over $1.3 billion in lost fines and restitution. Together, these actions showed how wealth and proximity to the president could buy not just access but relief from the law itself, while enforcement fell hardest on those without such ties. The law was less a limit on power than a tool in its hands.\
\
Immigration policy became a clear example of how money and politics shaped who felt the weight of the state. Early in the week, the administration briefly paused ICE raids in agriculture and hospitality, acknowledging that aggressive deportations were hurting farmers and hotel owners. Many of those industries were linked to major Trump donors. Within days, under pressure from hardliners, Trump reversed course and ordered raids to resume, aiming for 3,000 arrests a day, including at farms and hotels. At the same time, Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick announced a waitlist for a $5 million \'93Trump Card\'94 that would grant permanent residency, turning legal status into a luxury product. The administration also tried to cancel birthright citizenship for children of undocumented immigrants by executive order, a direct challenge to the Fourteenth Amendment now before the Supreme Court. Citizenship, in this vision, was no longer a simple matter of birth and law; it was stratified by wealth, origin, and ideology.\
