On the streets, dissent was both widespread and constrained. The \'93No Kings\'94 protests brought more than five million people into the streets at over 2,000 events, one of the largest coordinated demonstrations in U.S. history. Protesters carried American flags, quoted the Constitution, and invoked the Revolution\'92s rejection of monarchy. Their message was not abstract; it was aimed at a president who had just staged a $40 million military parade in Washington, D.C., on his birthday, with corporate sponsors and armored vehicles rolling past mostly empty bleachers. The contrast between the thin crowd at the parade and the vast, festive protests across the country suggested where public energy lay. Yet in several cities, that energy met force. In Los Angeles, police used teargas, foam bullets, and mounted officers to disperse crowds outside a federal building, declaring an \'93unlawful assembly\'94 that many never heard. In Salt Lake City, a confrontation involving an armed man and volunteer peacekeepers ended in a fatal shooting of a protester. In Florida, Governor Ron DeSantis told drivers they could legally run over protesters if they felt threatened by a crowd. Protest rights still existed on paper, but the cost of exercising them rose.\
\
The week also showed how quickly political violence can move from rhetoric to reality. In Minnesota, a gunman dressed as a police officer went to the homes of Democratic state representative Melissa Hortman and state senator John Hoffman. He killed Hortman and her husband and wounded Hoffman and his wife. The suspect, Vance Boelter, left behind a list of targets\'97mostly Democrats and abortion-rights advocates\'97and a manifesto steeped in right-wing grievances. State and federal authorities moved swiftly to arrest and charge him with murder and firearms offenses, and the Minnesota congressional delegation issued a bipartisan statement condemning the attack. Yet even as law enforcement treated the case as a politically motivated assassination, right-wing media figures and some elected officials rushed to recast it. They falsely labeled Boelter a leftist, blamed Democratic leaders for the violence, and spread conspiracy theories that reached millions of viewers. Senator Mike Lee posted and then deleted claims that the killer was a \'93Marxist,\'94 but he did not apologize. In this way, the same event that should have united the country against political murder became raw material for disinformation.\
