The courts, meanwhile, sent mixed signals about their willingness to check the executive and protect vulnerable groups. On one side, federal judges blocked the administration from canceling hundreds of NIH grants tied to diversity and LGBTQ research, calling the cuts \'93void and illegal\'94 and ordering funds restored. They halted mass firings in the Education Department\'92s Office for Civil Rights and blocked the EPA from canceling $600 million in environmental justice grants. A judge ordered the government to reinstate legal services for families separated under the earlier \'93zero tolerance\'94 policy, enforcing a settlement the administration had tried to sidestep. Another judge ordered the release on bail of Mahmoud Khalil, a Palestinian activist and green-card holder whom the government had detained for months in what the court saw as retaliation for his speech. And a federal appeals court refused to let the Justice Department represent Trump in his personal defamation appeal, drawing a line between the man and the office.\
